<br>
Most times with organ transplants its the rejection and rejection drugs that make the operation the most dangerous. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/ugukalaxegrinder.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Gukal Axegrinder</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(4/2/02 7:43:48 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: OT:  Cloning</span><hr size=1> I'm not inherently opposed to the process of cloning.  The specific application will make more of a difference to me.  <br>
<br>
BUT expect troubles ... when humans tinker (pardon to all gnomes present) with a complex system about which they have only the most fundamental knowledge ... there will inevitably be many unforeseen consequences.<br>
<br>
At a mimimum, I would expect the following eventually --<br>
<br>
1. new diseases and disorders until we discover that one of the genes governing eye color also influences certain immunities.<br>
<br>
2. fetal/infant deaths directly attributable to the tampering (offset somewhat by infants saved from certain death by the same tampering)<br>
<br>
3. Psychological shifts in society as man becomes increasing viewed as its own creator.  If the science ever became sophisticated enough, selecting options for your child as you would for your new car could have a significant impact on the whole experience.  I recently experienced the birth of my son and even in this modern age of medicine there survives an element of mystery that I appreciate.<br>
<br>
4.  As a pure layman, I take notice of the fact that as a percentage, the DNA of most life forms on this planet vary only a little.  However, the 2% of differences between a human and a dolphin (completely made-up percentage) seems to have a large impact on the outcome.  Thus, I would expect that after making a few modifications to some DNA -- every now and then -- you would end up with the birth of a life form that cannot properly be categorized as human.<br>
 <br>
In this sense, over time you'd expect that the human race as it exists today would be supplanted by minor &quot;improvements&quot;.  It seems that a species that engages in genetically altering itself will over time (perhaps a very long time) guarantee its own extinction.  I have not yet developed an opinion as to whether a successor species that improves (in some objective sense relative to its environment) upon humanity is a desirable thing.<br>
